    <title>How to watch Apple’s ‘Glowtime’ iPhone 16 event</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Picture of the Apple Glowtime event: a rainbow-colored Apple logo with rounded shapes overlapping behind and inside of it." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/2YhbopFx6mChLnkWTRwFi6Mwwpk=/160x0:1888x1152/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73570835/Glowtime.0.jpeg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Apple&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="i74rFC"&gt;The iPhone 16 is nigh as Apple prepares to &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/4/24232248/apple-event-september-iphone-16-date-time-live-stream-watch-how-to-rumors"&gt;debut its next smartphone lineup&lt;/a&gt; on Monday, September 9th, at 1PM ET / 10AM PT. The company is expected to officially announce four phones as usual, with two standard iPhone 16s and two iPhone 16 Pro models, all likely packed with &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/7/31/24209910/apple-intelligence-ios-18-preview-siri"&gt;Apple Intelligence&lt;/a&gt; AI features.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="gDVyi5"&gt;You can catch the livestream at &lt;a href="https://www.apple.com/"&gt;Apple’s own website&lt;/a&gt;, on &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uarNiSl_uh4"&gt;its YouTube channel&lt;/a&gt;, and even on an Apple TV. (Apple usually makes sure you see this when you scroll from the home screen of the Apple TV app, but you can search for “Apple Event” to find it, too.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="6isCmT"&gt;
